  "description": "Åke Thoriild Ljungfors was a Swedish scholar and educator. He was born on March 29, 1912, in Ängelholm, Sweden, to Vilhelm Ljungfors and Ester Thorsson. He married Maj Elgstedt in 1942. Ljungfors achieved his high school degree in Malmö in 1929, followed by a bachelor's degree from Lund University in 1934. He obtained a master's degree in 1936 and a PhD in 1941. Ljungfors worked as an intern at Hvitfeldtska in Gothenburg from 1942 to 1943 and held various teaching positions in Malmö and Gothenburg. Since 1946, he served as the Secretary and Advertising Director at Gothenburg City Theater. Ljungfors conducted research on the working conditions of classics on behalf of the Swedish Classical Association in 1942 and served as the chairman of Gothenburg's Younger District Teachers' Association from 1943 to 1946. He authored several articles and reviews in the press, including 'Malmö's recess 1524' (1941) and 'Bishop Brynoif Algotsson' (1942). Ljungfors had hobbies of book and stamp collecting.",
